> Question of the day: Do you have experience working in manufacturing, on the plant floor?  If so, which industry?  What do you think was their biggest hurdles to digital transformation?
@Walker Reynolds Yes. Out of school, I worked at a PCB assembly shop. Programming and Operating pick and place machines. When I took over my line, there were conveyors between each work cell (screen printer, pick and place, reflow oven) but none were operational. By the time I left there, I had them all connected and working together. Once I had a job up and running I spent the rest of my time researching my next job. As an engineer, I worked at a medical manufacturer for 3 years before moving to my current job. I'm no longer production support but I build and design machines for the floor.

At all previous employers, the biggest hurdle to digital transformation was lack of ambition. The PCB assembler and medical manufacturer did not forward think at all. Capital expenditure was rare. My current company is 100% on board. The only questions we have left are how. We are having a digital roadmap meeting this Friday! 😄

