@Luke Smaul @Walker Reynolds @zackscriven   Really inspired today! I christen today’s excellent Q&A with the title *Discussion on Digital Transformation as creating an ecosystem of value exchange, and the best approach to effect that change in manufacturing*.

@Mario Ishikawa Mario made a great comment that the difference between Walker and Luke was largely a difference in sales approach. Walker’s is an inside-out approach (starting with manufacturing operations) vs. Luke’s outside-in approach (knocking down the firewalls separating company and supply chain, company and consumers). 

Is it more effective to talk to executives about trends in increased value from data-driven plant operations, or from bringing suppliers and customers into the ecosystem? Is the 4.0 Product Manager a data analyst or an MVP (minimum viable product) designer defining value needs of end users? Listening, it seems the answer is some of both.

Luke’s statement--- “To revolutionize manufacturing, yes, we have to get the tech right, but also, we must alter a company’s business model.” 

I want to say …AND we have to openly acknowledge culture and company values, how these determine the way technology is applied, to empower people or against them. Consumer and employee trust in the business intent is important. Hence Luke’s story about (perversely) using sensor data to revoke machine warranty coverage. Walker once mentioned executives who view plant floor personnel as expendable. 

I do believe we 4.0 proponents need to be experts in helping companies identify and create value, how to align with values and incentivize the right things, how to avoid bad design and poor implementation. I’m not so convinced we can help those with entrenched shortsightedness and values coming from the Ferengi school of business.

