@Paulo Vitor is likely asking, what is the "Performance Level" of that PLC.

Performance level has a regulated definition that enables engineers to design systems with confidence that hazards to people, including death, have been mitigated.

If the PLC you mention doesn't talk of safety or performance levels, then it's likely out of scope for what Paulo is after.

@Jon Forbord, @Andy, @Mario Ishikawa, @AristótelesTN - wow I guess it would be better to try and share something here instead 🙂 What I'll refer to here is more related to the development of a digital strategy itself. Not an apples-to-apples comparison to a DTMA by any means, and I'd love to discuss how a DTMA would relate to such an activity. These numbers all assume that the scope includes marketing, consumer insights, e-com, sales, HR, R&D and a whole bunch of other stuff on top of the manufacturing and supply chain pieces. 

Important to keep in mind that this will of course vary from organization to organization. Needs, goals and circumstances will always be different, so it is NOT a universal truth in any way shape or form. So, making it clear that this is my personal *experience * and not more than that - if you reach out to your average management consulting firm to help out with crafting a *digital strategy*, you tend to get offers back in the range of a timeline of 15-20 weeks and a cost of $500,000 - $800,000. A rough estimate would be that the cost is about $40,000 / week. And be very sure that there will be multiple occasions along the ride that additional offers will be presented for "add-on services".

