@Jon Forbord - To be clear, I didn't say that the other industries weren't struggling at all, I just said that they seem to be much more successful. 

In the early days of Spruik Technologies, we integrated Outsystems (the biggest and most prolific of the low code platforms.) We were trying to make it work for Mfg (next to impossible because it doesn't have a time series component, among other issues, like being tied to MS and .Net - see cloud native/agnostic comment above), but we were inundated with the success stories and talked to many, many people from those industries that had created massive, sustainable transformation at the enterprise level.

That's my experience...

@RickBullotta - Fair point, but as you and I have discussed - there is significant difference between a product developed by people that have tried and failed to implement the status quo and one that is developed by code jockeys, with no industry experience, that built a solution and then went looking for a problem to solve.

The latter will almost always need the engine of which you speak because they will be constantly spending pre-sales capital on convincing prospects that it "can" solve the fringe use case instead of just demonstrating to that prospect that it "does" solve for those use cases. 

When you can repeatedly show what you "do" instead of grinding one-off PoCs to show what you "can do," you tend to get more "pull" from your client base. You still need the engine, but a 4-cylinder will do just fine...

